You are pulling in a **collection** for your `$eventid` variable in this line:

    $eventid = Event::select(&#39;id&#39;)-&gt;orderBy(&#39;startdate&#39;)-&gt;where(&#39;startdate&#39;,&#39;&gt;&#39;, now())-&gt;take(1)-&gt;get();
   
`$eventid` is a collection of **Event** objects numbering in total 1.  To get the id of the *first* event after your start date, try the following:

    $event = Event::where(&#39;startdate&#39;,&#39;&gt;&#39;, now())-&gt;first();
    $eventid = isset($event)? $event-&gt;id : 0;

You could chain this and put the id at the end (`-&gt;first()-&gt;id`), but you may not have an event after this starting date, and thus it would fail.

The difference in this answer vs your original code, is that by using `first`, you pull a single object that will have an `id` field.  Doing it with `get()` as you did, it will be a collection, and not have an id field, and thus will fail your `where()` method on the **Speaker** query.

Note, you may also wish to revise the query parameters.  The way you have it now, and the way I wrote it with `first()` will give you the first event after the startdate. You may want something further down the line if you have multiple events. You could add more detail on the query if this is the case.

Your `$eventid` variable is a collection. `find` works fine to get you the instance of the model but in where clause you are supplying collection instead of a variable. and thus it&#39;s not working. And why are you using `get` and then `find`?? use simply `first` 

    $event = Event::where(&#39;startdate&#39;,&#39;&gt;&#39;, now())-&gt;orderBy(&#39;startdate&#39;)-&gt;first();
    $speaker = Speaker::where(&#39;event_id&#39;, &#39;=&#39;, $event-&gt;id)-&gt;get();
